\begin_layout Section
Email
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Architecture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The email architecture is based on several components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Message User Agent (
\series bold
MUA
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Message Submission Agent (
\series bold
MSA
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Message Transfer Agent (
\series bold
MTA
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Message Delivery Agent (
\series bold
MDA
\series default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice software implementations often merge MSA/MTA and MTA/MDA into
 the same component.
 Instead of a MUA, users tend to retrieve emails through web clients, e.g.
 Gmail.
 Emails are delivered through the 
\series bold
SMTP
\series default
 protocol, while clients can retrieve emails in two ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
POP
\series default
, where the connection is enstablished only when fetching messages, which
 are stored locally and then deleted from the server
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
IMAP
\series default
, where the connection is kept on while the user is browsing emails, which
 can be cloned locally (and optionally deleted from the server).
 Multiple clients can access the same mailbox
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Message format
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An email is made of three parts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
envelop
\series default
.
 Contains minimal info about sender/receiver that can be quickly processed
 by SMTP servers along the route.
 Its main fields are MAIL FROM, i.e.
 where to send back the message in case of failure, and RCPT TO, which is
 the receiver address
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
header
\series default
.
 Contains meta information.
 It is structured into fields such as FROM, TO, CONTENT-TYPE, and RETURN-PATH;
 may contain extra fields for security checks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
body
\series default
.
 Text of the message
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
MIME
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By default, SMTP supports only ASCII content.
 The 
\series bold
MIME
\series default
 standard allows text in character sets other than ASCII, non-text attachments,
 and message bodies with multiple parts.
 MIME is completely transparent to the email system, since it provides a
 way to encode and decode this content at the endpoint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Privacy and security risks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three main risks associated with emails: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
spamming
\series default
.
 Unwanted or undesirable email messages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
tracking
\series default
.
 The user reading an email may reveal sensitive informations, e.g.
 if the address is valid, IP of victim, or browser and devices used
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
phishing
\series default
.
 A social engineering technique where an attacker sends a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spoofed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 message designed to trick a victim into revealing sensitive information.
 General phishing is easy to automatically detect, while spear phishing
 is targeted to a category of users or even a single user, making it harder
 to detect
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Validation systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
SPF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One big problem with emails is that the body and the envelope of the email
 are somewhat separated entities.
 The body is built by the client that creates the email, while the envelope
 is made on the server through the interaction between client and server.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
SPF
\series default
 can detect email spam through verification of the sender IP addresses.
 The domain publishes a DNS (TXT) record containing a list of IPs allowed
 to send messages, while the SMTP server validates the sender IP inside
 the RETURN PATH field.
 However it does not validate the FROM field, which can be easily spoofed,
 and may break when a message is forwarded.
 Furthermore, SPF does not validate the email content, which may be tampered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
DKIM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that SPF only works on the email envelope, 
\series bold
DKIM
\series default
 was introduced to specify how some parts of the message can be cryptographicall
y signed in order to avoid their content to be tampered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Domain administrators define from which domains users are allowed to receive
 emails.
 The sender's server signs the message using his private key, while the
 domain published a DNS (TXT) record with info regarding his public key.
 Selectors can define different keys for multiple purposes/subdomains, and
 the receiver is then able to validate the message.
 However messages may be modified between server exchanges, and does not
 provide confidentiality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
DMARC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DMARC extends SPF/DKIM through policies, which define a domain email authenticat
ion practices and provide instructions on how to receive emails.
 In other words, domain administrator publish DNS (TXT) records with rules
 on what to do when a message fails DKIM/SPF and how to report abuses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DMARC checks if the message header has proper 
\series bold
domain alignment
\series default
, expanding what SPF and DKIM already do.
 In particular, for SPF it checks if the domain in the From field correspond
 to the domain in the return-path field; for DKIM it checks if the domain
 in the From field correspond to the domain in the DKIM header field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
ARC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
DKIM and SPF may break when a message is forwarded or altered by other SMTP
 servers.
 
\series bold
ARC
\series default
 provides a way to authenticate the entire chain traversed by the message,
 while SPF and DKIM authenticate only the original sender.
 This can be done using three additional headers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
ARC-Authentication-Results
\series default
: a combination of an instance number and the results of the SPF, DKIM,
 and DMARC validation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
ARC-Seal
\series default
: A combination of an instance number, a DKIM-like signature of the previous
 ARC-Seal headers, and the validity of the prior ARC entries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
ARC-Message-Signature
\series default
: A combination of an instance number and a DKIM-like signature of the entire
 message except for the ARC-Seal headers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each hop in the chain signs the message.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Security for end users
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
PGP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PGP is a software which provides cryptographic privacy and authentication
 for data communication.
 It is used for signing, encrypting/decrypting texts, e-mails, and files.
 PGP and similar software follow the OpenPGP standard.
 Each public key is bound to a username or an e-mail address.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
confidentiality
\series default
.
 A symmetric (session) key is generated by the sender and used to encrypt
 the message.
 This session key is encrypted with the receiver's pubblic key and is sent
 along with the encrypted message
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
authentication
\series default
 and 
\series bold
integrity
\series default
.
 The sender computes the hash from the plaintext and then creates a digital
 signature using his private key.
 This proves that the message was not tampered and sent by the same person
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several RFCs defining how to embed the signature and encrypted
 content inside a message: it can be appended as an attachment or at the
 end of the message.
 However, different clients behave in different ways.
 The MIME/PGP subtype mitigates this issue, but it is still kind of a mess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both when encrypting messages and when verifying signatures, it is critical
 that the public key used to send messages to someone actually does belong
 to the intended recipient.
 From its first version, PGP expands on the concept of 
\series bold
web of trust
\series default
.
 Each client maintains two 
\series bold
keyring
\series default
: the public keyring contains all the public keys of other trusted (signed)
 PGP users, while the private keyring contains the public/private key pairs
 of the current user.
 Other users may also trust these keys if they trust who signed them, or
 if they are trusted by 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 users.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
S/MIME
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending on MIME, it provides the same security properties of PGP: authenticati
on, message integrity, non-repudiation of origin, confidentiality.
 However, its trust model is based on X.509 certificates and CAs.
 Several RFC define new MIME subtypes, and the sender may include several
 certificate (other than itself) to correctly enforce the trust.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Web vulnerabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
OWASP
\series default
 initiative provides some best practices to be adapted in order to make
 systems more secure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Broken Access Control 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Access control enforces policy such that users cannot act outside of their
 intended permissions.
 Failures typically lead to unauthorized information disclosure, modification,
 or destruction of all data or performing a business function outside the
 user's limits.
 Common access control vulnerabilities include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
bypassing access control checks by modifying the URL, internal application
 state, or the HTML page
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
permitting viewing or editing someone else's account, by providing its unique
 identifier
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
accessing API with missing access controls for POST, PUT and DELETE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
elevation of privilege.
 Acting as a user without being logged in or acting as an admin when logged
 in as a user
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CORS misconfiguration allows API access from unauthorized/untrusted origins
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
force browsing to authenticated pages as an unauthenticated user or to privilege
d pages as a standard user
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Access control is only effective in trusted server-side code or server-less
 API, where the attacker cannot modify the access control check or metadata.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
except for public resources, deny by default
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
minimize CORS usage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
disable web server directory listing and ensure file metadata, e.g.
 .git, and backup files are not present within web roots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
log access control failures, alert admins when appropriate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
rate limit API access to minimize the harm from automated attack tooling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Injection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An application is vulnerable to attack when user-supplied data is not validated,
 filtered, or sanitized by the application, and hostile data is directly
 used or concatenated.
 Source code review is the best method of detecting if applications are
 vulnerable to injections.
 Automated testing of parameter such as headers, URL, cookies, and input
 fields is strongly encouraged.
 Preventing injection requires keeping data separate from commands and queries:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
use server-side input validation.
 This is not a complete defense as many applications require special characters,
 such as text areas or APIs for mobile applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for any residual dynamic queries, escape special characters using the specific
 escape syntax for that interpreter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
use LIMIT and other SQL controls within queries to prevent mass disclosure
 of records in case of SQL injection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
XSS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The attacker manages to inject JavaScript code, which is executed in the
 browser of the victim, inside a web application.
 As always it stems from improper sanitization of user inputs.
 Once users visit a comprosimed web app, they will rececive the malicious
 payload.
 A typical way to perform a XSS attack is to embed some kind of script into
 a snippet of html.
 There are three common variants of XSS attacks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
reflected
\series default
: the website includes data from the incoming HTTP request into the web
 page (without proper sanitization).
 Users are tricked into visiting an honest website with an URL prepared
 by the attacker 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
stored
\series default
: the payload is permanently stored server-side, e.g.
 inside the database of the web application.
 Whena user loads the page, his web browser executes the script
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
DOM-based
\series default
: the payload is embedded into the web page on browser-side.
 This means that server-side detection techniques do not work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any user input must be preprocessed before it is used inside the page: HTML
 special characters must be properly encoded before being inserted into
 the page.
 Against DOM-based XSS, developers can use Trusted Types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
CSRF 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
CSRF
\series default
 is similar to XSS, but the attacker abuse the automatic attachment of cookies
 to requests done by browsers, in order to perform arbitrary actions within
 the session established by the victim.
 Assuming that the victim is authenticated on the target website:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the victim visits the attacker's website
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
this page triggers a request towards the victim website, e.g.
 forms automatically submitted via JavaScript 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the cookie identifying this session is automatically attached by the browser
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Websites can guard against CSRF by generating a token per user session,
 embedded inside forms (as hidden field) or as a cookie, and requiring a
 matching value when performing sensitive operations.
 This token may be generated at every page load (limiting the validity timeframe
 of leaked values) or once on session start (improves usability when navigating
 the same site).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
CSP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Originally developed to mitigate content injection vulnerabilities like
 XSS, 
\series bold
CSP
\series default
 can be used to restrict which resources can be loaded by a web page, and
 limit their origin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
SSRF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SSRF flaws occur whenever a web application is fetching a remote resource
 without validating the user-supplied URL.
 It allows an attacker to coerce the application to send a crafted request
 to an unexpected destination, even when protected by a firewall, VPN, or
 another type of network access control list (ACL).
 Developers can prevent SSRF by implementing some or all the following defense
 in depth controls:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
segment remote resource access functionality in separate networks, to reduce
 the impact of SSRF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
enforce 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

deny by default‚Äù firewall policies or network access control rules to block
 all but essential intranet traffic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
sanitize and validate all client-supplied input data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
enforce the URL schema, port, and destination with a positive allow list
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
disable HTTP redirections 
\end_layout

