\begin_layout Part*
Privacy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Blockchain technologies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A blockchains is said to be 
\series bold
permitionless
\series default
 if a user can join or leave the network whenever he wants, without having
 to be pre-approved by any central entity.
 There is no central owner of the network and software, and identical copies
 of the ledger are distributed to all the nodes in the network.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead a 
\series bold
permissioned
\series default
 blockchain, transaction validators, i.e.
 nodes, have to be pre-selected by a network administrator (who sets the
 rules for the ledger) to be able to join the network.
 This allows to easily verify the identity of the network participants,
 but at the same time its participants have to put trust in the central
 authority to select reliable network nodes.
 Furthermore, there can be 
\series bold
open permitioned
\series default
 blockchains, which can be viewed by anyone but only authorized participants
 can generate transactions, and 
\series bold
closed permitioned
\series default
 blockchains, where access is restricted and only the administrator can
 generate transactions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bitcoin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bitcoin network is based on a 
\series bold
decentralized identity management
\series default
.
 Rather than having a central authority which registers users, anyone can
 generate a new 
\series bold
pseudo-identity
\series default
 (i.e.
 an address) at any time.
 Wallets are softwares which can generate public/private key pairs, with
 a corresponding address.
 Bitcoins are sent to an address, by registering the transaction on the
 blockchain.
 Identities based on addresses can guarantee 
\series bold
pseudonymity
\series default
.
 In this context we can define anonymity as a combination of pseudonynity
 and 
\series bold
unlikability
\series default
.
 We can reach unlikability if the following properties hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it should be hard to link together different addresses of the same user
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it should be hard to link together different transactions made by the same
 user
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
it should be hard to link the sender of a payment to its recipient
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main idea is that we do not know who really is behind a given address.
 However, in practice, it's possible to deanonymize the Bitcoin network.
 There are services that requires a real identity, and the blockchain is
 public, so that any user can trace all the transactions of any other user.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

taint
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a Bitcoin transaction evaluates the association between an address and
 earlier transaction addresses.
 A possible approach to anonymize Bitcoin transactions is to use the 
\series bold
mixing
\series default
 technique: users send their money to an anonymous service and it will send
 back someone else coins.
 However, in case of failure or if access to funds is denied, there is no
 recourse.
 An alternative solution is to have a decentralized mixing service, where
 different peers self-organizes in order to create the transaction, but
 it may not be easy to find other participants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Zerocoin and Zerocash
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Designed as an extension to the Bitcoin protocol, 
\series bold
Zerocoin
\series default
 improves transactions anonymity by having coin-mixing capabilities natively
 built into the protocol.
 However, it is not currently compatible with Bitcoin.
 The underlying crypto relies on zero-knowledge proofs.
 In order to spend a Zerocoin, a user needs to prove that he owns that coin
 and it has not been already spent.
 Meanwhile 
\series bold
Zerocash
\series default
 can provide additional anonymity by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shielding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the amount transacted.
 Unlike Zerocoin, Zerocash requires an initial setup by a trusted entity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Other cryptocurrencies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Bitcoin
\series default
 cash and 
\series bold
Litecoin
\series default
 are based on the original SHA-256 PoW algorithm with small adjustements.
 The foremost increased the bock size limit to 
\begin_inset Formula $8MB$
\end_inset

 to reduce transaction fees and improve confirmation times, while the latter
 offers a faster transaction speed than Bitcoin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead 
\series bold
Algorand
\series default
 achieves consensus with another kind of algorithm named Proof-of-Stakes,
 where a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

committee
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is choosen at random and its participants have to vote for a new block.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Privacy Preserving Data Mining
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data and knowledge extracted by data mining techniques represents a key
 asset to the society.
 Laws and regulations require that some collected data must be made public,
 which leads to the problem of 
\series bold
inference control
\series default
: protecting private data while publishing useful information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
access control: protecting information from unauthorized access and use
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
disclosure control: modify data in order to prevent third-parties working
 with these data to recognize individuals (in the data)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to anonymize the data we must first remove every 
\series bold
Personally Identifying Information
\series default
 (PII).
 However, an attacker may be able to join other fields with additional sources
 and de-anonymize the dataset.
 
\series bold
PPDM
\series default
 aims to reduce unauthorized access of private information, while retaining
 the same functions as a normal data mining method for discovering useful
 knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Microdata and macrodata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Microdata
\series default
 represents a series of records, containing information on an individual
 unit such as a person or an institution.
 Macrodata instead contains computed data, e.g statistics.
 Quasi-identifiers such as 5-digit ZIP code or gender can be used for linking
 anonymized dataset with other datasets, while sensitive attributes, e.g.
 medical records or salaries, are always released directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
K-anonymity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Privacy risks appear when you can reidentify a record.
 A database is 
\begin_inset Formula $k\text{-anonymous}$
\end_inset

 with respect to quasi-identifier attributes if there exist at least 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 records in the database having the same values.
 This means that individuals cannot be distinguished from 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

 others.
 This can be achieved through two techniques:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
generalization
\series default
: replace quasi-identifiers with less specific, but semantically consistent
 values
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
suppression
\series default
: do not release a value at all in some sensitive tuple.
 Useful when generalization causes too much information loss, common with
 outliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective is to generalize or to suppress data in a given database until
 it becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $k\text{-anonymized}$
\end_inset

, while incurring a minimal loss of information.
 The cost incurred is considerably low compared to other anonymity methods
 such as cryptographic solutions.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $k\text{-anonymity}$
\end_inset

 this is an operational definition of a privacy mechanism rather than a
 mathematical definition of a privacy property; it is not much help if 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 individuals all possess the same sensitive attribute.
 It is susceptible to common attacks (unsorted matching, complementary release,
 homogeneity) and can cause high utility loss if it is employed in high-dimensio
nal data and/or if the released data has already undergone anonymization
 more than once.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
L-diversity and T-Completeness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\text{L-}diversity$
\end_inset

 builds upon k-anonymity and fix one of its most obvious flaws.
 Let's say that all records with the same quasi-identifier tuple are in
 the same bucket.
 If all sensitive values are the same within a bucket, we might leak private
 information.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{L-}diversity$
\end_inset

 states that each bucket must have at least 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 distinct sensitive values.
 Of course, each bucket should contain at least 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 records, since it implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{l-}anonymity$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even with the new added uncertainty, an attacker might have a strong suspicion
 about his victim sensitive information.
 Requiring that sensitive attributes are diverse is not enough.
 We need to also require that their distribution is roughly the same as
 the rest of the data, leading to the core idea behind 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{t-}closeness$
\end_inset

.
 This way, the attacker's knowledge can't change too much from the baseline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it is hard to quantify the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

amount of privacy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 obtained with a given choice of parameter, and the utility loss is significant.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{K-}anonymity$
\end_inset

 and its variants are based on the concept of Personally Identifiable Informatio
n (
\series bold
PII
\series default
), which has no guarantee and has no precise definition.
 These approach can still leak sensitive information, since it is assumed
 that attackers do not know other information about their target.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential privacy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In cryptography, 
\series bold
differential privacy
\series default
 aims to provide means to maximize the accuracy of queries from statistical
 databases while minimizing the chances of identifying its records.
 Since this is a probabilistic concept, any differentially private mechanism
 is necessarily random.
 For a given value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the amount of noise introduced, there will be many differentially private
 algorithms for achieving the task, some with better accuracy than others.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of dataset, if the effect of an arbitrary single substitution in
 the database is small enough, the query result cannot be used to infer
 much about any single individual, and therefore provides privacy.
 In other words, differential privacy gives each individual roughly the
 same privacy that would result from having their data removed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Social networks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Netflix deanonymization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Netflix, in October 
\begin_inset Formula $2006$
\end_inset

, offered a 
\begin_inset Formula $\$1\text{m}$
\end_inset

 prize for a better recommender algorithm and published the viewer ratings
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $500,000$
\end_inset

 subscribers with their names removed.
 Two researchers at the time showed that many subscribers could be reidentified
 by comparing the anonymous records with preferences publicly expressed
 in the IMDB.
 This is partly due to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

long tail
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 effect: once you disregard the top 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

 or so movies everyone watches, people's viewing preferences are pretty
 unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Social network deanonymization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A network can be partially or totally deanonymized when the attacker, starting
 from a re-identication of a subset of the nodes from an auxiliary network
 that partially overlaps with the original network, gains knowledge about
 the edges of the graph (representing the network).
 For instance, we can consider the partial deanonymization of the Twitter
 graph using the Flickr graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Privacy concerns in social medias
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People posting information by themselves on social networks increase the
 probability to be subject to threats such as malwares and stalking, leading
 to several privacy issues.
 All of this information about an user can be combined with social engineering
 techniques and lead to identity theft, be used in phishing, and other type
 of attacks.
 Often a user is not aware of the amount of information that is shared in
 social networks.
 Another problem is that creating a fake account is often easy, and can
 be used to lure other users in doing something wrong in order to compromise
 their privacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore users accept people as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

friends
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that do not know at all just to enlarge their group, but at the same time
 allows such people to access their personal information and pictures.
 Privacy controls are within the hand of users, but the majority of users
 think that the information about themselves do not represent a privacy
 risk at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Privacy legislation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Privacy By Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Privacy by Design (
\series bold
PbD
\series default
) is an approach to system engineering which promotes privacy through the
 whole engineering process.
 This means designing data so it does not need protection.
 According to PbD supporters 
\series bold
data minimization
\series default
 is the most important safeguard in protecting personally identiable information
 and the use of cryptography, de-identication techniques and data aggregation
 are absolutely critical.
 However PbD is similar to voluntary compliance, and its concept does not
 focus on the role of the actual data holder, but on that of the system
 designer.
 This role is not known in privacy law, so the concept of Privacy by Design
 is not based in law.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
GDPR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The European Commission presented a proposal to ensure a coherent framework
 and a harmonized system in EU matters, which goes under the name of General
 Data Protection Regulations (
\series bold
GDPR
\series default
).
 Here, two roles can be distinguished: the 
\series bold
data controller
\series default
, which is the person or body that, alone or jointly with others, determines
 the purpose and means of the processing of personal data; the 
\series bold
data processor
\series default
, which is a legal person or body which processes personal data on behalf
 of the controller.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important aspect is that GDPR applies only for pseudonymized data.
 In this context, 
\series bold
pseudonymization
\series default
 means the processing of personal data in such a way that the personal data
 can no longer be attributed to a specic data subject without the use of
 additional information, provided that such additional information is kept
 separately and is subject to technical and organizational measure to ensure
 that it can not be attributed to an identifiable natural person.
 The GDPR defines the following characteristics of the regulations for privacy
 for individuals:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
easier access to your own data
\series default
: users will have more information on how their data is processed, available
 in a clear and understandable way
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
right to data portability
\series default
: it will be easier to transfer your personal data between service providers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
right to be forgotten
\series default
: when you no longer want your data to be processed, and provided that there
 are no legitimate grounds for retaining it, the data will be deleted
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
right to know when your data has been hacked
\series default
: companies and organizations must notify the national supervisory authority
 of serious data breaches as soon as possible so that users can take appropriate
 measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
data protection by design and by default
\series default
: data protection is designed into the development of business processes
 for products and services, and the default settings should be those that
 provide the most privacy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
stronger enforcement of the rules
\series default
: data protection authorities will be able to fine companies who do not
 comply with EU rules up to 4% of their global annual turnover
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the characteristics of the regulations for privacy for business defined
 by the GDPR are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
one continent, one law
\series default
: the regulation will establish one single set of rules which will make
 easier and cheaper for companies to do business in the EU
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
one-stop-shop
\series default
: business will only have to deal with one single supervisory authority.
 It will favor the cooperation between the data protection authorities on
 issues of interest for all of Europe
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
european rules on european soil
\series default
: the companies outside of Europe will have to apply the same rules when
 offering services in EU
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
risk-based approach
\series default
: the rules will avoid a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one-size-fits-all
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 obligation and rather tailor them to the respective risks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
rules fit for innovation
\series default
: data protection by design will guarantee that data protection safeguards
 are built into products and services from the earliest stage of development.
 Furthermore, privacy-friendly techniques such as pseudonymization, anonymizatio
n, and encryption will be encouraged
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Data Protection Officer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Data Protection Officer (
\series bold
DPO
\series default
) is a designed person within an organization that collects the personal
 data of Union citizens, who is responsible for making sure that the organizatio
n follows the new regulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
inform and advise the owner of the treatment about their obligations under
 the European regulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
check the implementation and application of the regulations and provide
 opinions on the assessment of the impact on data protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
acts as a contact point about any issue related to the processing of their
 data or the exercise of their rights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A DPO must be compulsorily appointed by government departments and agencies
 (with the exception of judicial authorities), all person whose main business
 consists of treatments which require regular and systematic monitoring
 of those concerned, and all persons whose main business is processing sensitive
 data concerning health or sex life, genetic, judicial and biometrics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Italy regulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Italy with the legislative decree of June 30th 2003 established the regulatio
ns and laws for protecting sensitive data according to the fast spreading
 of application technologies in the world.
 In particular, the data considered sensible by the regulations are the
 following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
sensitive data
\series default
: personal data revealing ethic origin, religious beliefs, philosophical
 or other beliefs, political opinions, health and sex life, etc
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
judicial data
\series default
: personal data relating to criminal records, the register of offense-related
 administrative sanctions and the relevant current charges, or as an accused
 or suspected person of the criminal procedure code
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such data needs to be processed according to the following rules: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
anyone has the right to protection of personal data concerning him
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the processing of personal data will be respect for human rights and fundamental
 freedoms and dignity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the information systems and programs are congured to minimize the use of
 personal data and identication data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rights of individuals data are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the right of access to personal data, including the right to obtain conrmation
 of the existence of data concerning him, the right to have their communication
 in intelligible form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the right of cancellation, anonymization or blocking of data processed in
 violation of the law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the right to oppose, for legitimate and documented reasons to the treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Italy there is a collegian body composed of four members elected by Parliamen
t called 
\series bold
Garante
\series default
.
 Such entity must communicate data processing and preliminary consent of
 specic actions such as the usage of detection systems of biometric, data
 processed with the help of electronic instruments to dene the prole or
 personality, etc.
 The major problems for companies and administrations are that they have
 to follow a well dened and strict set of rules regarding non disclosure
 of information and must have an explicit consent from the users in order
 to process the data for a specic and explicit purpose.
 Another complications may come from 
\series bold
Bring your own device
\series default
 approach, where companies monitors their employees together with their
 devices for security reasons, but this must always be done in accordance
 with the law.
\end_layout

